\begin_layout Section
Elimination II
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Geometric interpretation of a system with 3 variables and 3 equations:
 Each equation represents a plane,
 to solve the system is to find the point at the intersection of all three planes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Are there any obvious questions that arise from this interpretation?
 (Expected answer:
 What if the three planes don't all cross at a point?
 Rebuttal:
 How could that happen?)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Range of things that could happen:
 Two planes could be parallel,
 or two planes could coincide,
 or even though no two planes are parallel maybe they don't cross at a point.
 Draw examples of all cases you can think of (counting the usual one,
 I see 5 where all planes are distinct:
 point,
 line,
 parallel lines,
 Z,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\equiv$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Trick question:
 Does every (single) linear equation 
\begin_inset Formula $ax+by+cz=d$
\end_inset

 correspond to a plane in 3d?
 (No because 
\begin_inset Formula $0=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $0=1$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Anyway,
 let's go back to the things that could happen geometrically and see how they happen in equations.
 Here is a system that corresponds to the parallel line case:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{rrrrrrr}
x & + & 2y & + & 3z & = & 6\\
2x & + & 2y & + & 2z & = & 6\\
3x & + & 4y & + & 5z & = & 12
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

Do the elimination,
 get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{rrrrrrr}
x & + &  & - & z & = & -3\\
 &  & y & + & 2z & = & 3\\
 &  &  &  & 0 & = & 0
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Meaning:
 What we're trying to find out is,
 what 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 can we plug in to make all of these equalities true?
 Well,
 the last one is true no matter what,
 so we only need to focus on the other ones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
If you think about it,
 you can pick whatever value you want for 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 This value will then determine a value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 that will make the equation true,
 and that value and only that value will work.
 Therefore,
 we have an infinitude of solutions,
 one for each value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
We represent this infinitude of solutions as follows.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free variable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 and the general solution is 
\begin_inset Formula $(-3+z,3-2z,z)$
\end_inset

.
 This means that for every value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 that we plug in here we get a distinct solution,
 and every solution is obtained from plugging some value of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Do the other two cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout point
Parallel lines is just changing,
 say,
 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

,
 and now the last equation becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $0=-6$
\end_inset

,
 and no value of 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 that we plug into the system will possibly make this statement become true!
 So every tuple is immediately disqualified from being a solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout point
Z consists of replacing the LHS of the third equation by the LHS of (say) the first equation.
 Very quickly get 
\begin_inset Formula $0=6$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

