\begin_layout Section
Matrix Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
It's convenient to abstract a bit from the way that we write systems.
 Carrying around the same variables all the time is kind of annoying and doesn't really add anything,
 especially since we always write them in the same place.
 Thus,
 we abstract away from the variable,
 and rewrite a system like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{rrrrrrr}
x & + & 2y & + & 3z & = & 18\\
x & + & 3y & + & 2z & = & 17\\
3x & + & 2y & + & z & = & 22
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

in what is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

augmented matrix notation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{rcrcrc|rc}
1 &  & 2 &  & 3 &  &  & 18\\
1 &  & 3 &  & 2 &  &  & 17\\
3 &  & 2 &  & 1 &  &  & 22
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
The vertical bar is only decoration (it's the namesake augmentation) – the underlying structure is called a 
\emph on
matrix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Definition:
 A matrix is a rectangular table whose entries are numbers.
 They are usually denoted in one of the following two ways:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3\\
4 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix}\text{ or }\begin{pmatrix}1 & 1 & 2\\
3 & 5 & 8\\
-1 & -2 & -3
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
General matrix of width 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and height 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

,
 abbreviated to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (note that height then width!):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{12} & \cdots & a_{1m}\\
a_{21} & a_{22} & \cdots & a_{2m}\\
\vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots\\
a_{n1} & a_{n2} & \cdots & a_{nm}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Note that the matrix is usually written with an upper-case letter,
 and its entries are written with the corresponding lower-case letter,
 with the subscript being two numbers:
 the row,
 then the column.
 Usually mathematicians juxtapose them,
 as in 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}$
\end_inset

,
 but if this becomes ambiguous,
 you can write a comma to separate them,
 e.g.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a_{11,12}$
\end_inset

.
 This will not happen very often in this class.
\end_layout

