\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Define 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row-reduced matrix
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

row-reduced echelon form
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

echelon form
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
 Every row is either zeros or starts with a single 1,
 called a pivot;
 every entry above a pivot is a zero,
 and the pivots are going 
\begin_inset Formula $\searrow$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Recap Gauss-Jordan elimination:
 Apply the three elementary operations (swap two rows,
 multiply a row by a nonzero number,
 add a multiple of a row to another) to the matrix until it's in row reduced form.
 If there's a 
\begin_inset Formula $0=1$
\end_inset

 row,
 the system has no solution.
 Otherwise:
 The columns with no pivots are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

free variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the columns with pivots are 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

determined variables
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Introduce a parameter for each free variable,
 and for each determined variable,
 use the row it corresponds to to solve for this variable in terms of the free variables.
\end_layout

